<DOCNO> AP890901-0015 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
more than 50 million us urine tests performed 
each year with simple chemical dipsticks cost more than 150 
million and many are unnecessary medical researchers say 
two studies published in fridays journal of the american medical 
association found that dipstick urinalysis the most commonly used 
urine test is unjustified for healthy young men and women though 
it may be useful for screening patients 60 years or older for 
unsuspected urinary problems 
dipstick urinalysis is one of the most frequently ordered tests 
by internists and family practitioners for urinary tract disorders 
ranging from infection to malignancy 
the test involves dipping a chemically treated stick into a urine 
sample changes in color on the chemically treated sticks can 
indicate the presence of sugar proteins blood and other substances 
that may point to possible bacterial infections or other bladder and 
kidney problems 
about 30 percent of all office visits to internists generate a 
dipstick urinalysis resulting in more than 50 million tests each 
year said the studies by the us preventive services task force 
at 3 per test dipsticks add more than 150 million annually to 
the nations healthcare bill the authors said 
in both studies the authors said pregnant women should be 
screened for urinary problems but they recommended using more 
sensitive tests such as urine cultures and microscopic examinations 
rather than dipstick urinalysis 
the first study conducted by dr steffie woolhander and 
colleagues at harvard medical school in boston looked at the 
effectiveness of dipstick urinalysis for detecting blood and protein 
in the urine 
the authors concluded that the benefits of screening symptomfree 
young adults are outweighed by the risks of following up false 
positives with further and more invasive testing 
but they said such tests may be appropriate for men and women 
over 60 because they have a higher disease prevalence the 
researchers recommended further study to determine the effectiveness 
of such screening 
the second study by dr richard j pels and colleagues at 
harvard found that dipstick testing of adults under 60 for evidence 
of bacterial urinary tract infection is also unwarranted for similar 
reasons 
but they said dipstick screening for bacteria may be appropriate 
for women who are over 60 years of age or diabetic 
both studies based their findings on a review and analysis of 
medical literature including data from five populationbased 
studies 
these studies showed that fewer than 15 percent to 2 percent of 
young adults with positive blood or protein dipstick results 
actually had a serious and treatable urinary tract disease 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

