<TEXT>
an agreement between u s west communications and 
regulatory officials will give refunds of 46 million to colorado 
consumers this year and increase telephone rates by more than 85 
million beginning in 1992 
the agreement was reached thursday by u s west the state office 
of consumer council and the state public utilities commission the 
commission was to hold a hearing on the settlement today in denver 
the refund stems from a february 1989 commission order requiring 
u s west to return money collected under federallymandated 
depreciation rates that later were overturned by the us supreme 
court 
customers who paid bills between 1985 and 1989 will get a refund 
about equal to the local service portion of one months telephone 
bill the company said the refunds will appear as credits 
probably in november bills the company said 
the company sought the rate increase to upgrade equipment 
especially for rural customers the size of the rate increase for 
individual consumers hasnt been set yet u s west has proposed 
phasing in a hike of less than a dollar a month on every phone bill 
in the state 
were delighted with this settlement said ron binz director 
of the consumer counsel office it means telephone customers get 
the refund theyre entitled to and the states rural customers get 
modern telephone service 
jim smith a vice president for u s west communications said the 
agreement would allow the company to modernize equipment across the 
state 
switching operations in 84 communities need to be modernized 
officials said but the companys regular equipment replacement 
budget can handle only four to six offices a year 
the improvements will allow for a variety of new services such as 
automatic call forwarding and transmission of computer data over 
telephone lines u s west said 
