a team of 100 people in bangkok have 
baked a 3ton chinese mooncake which they say is the largest ever 
made 
mooncakes made of sweet pastry and decorated with chinese 
characters are traditionally given as symbols of good will in 
chinese communities to mark the lunar festival 
the festival sept 14 commemorates chinese empress chang euh 
who according to legend ascended to the moon to watch over the 
world and protect it from tyranny 
the mooncake unveiled thursday was baked at a bangkok department 
store by chefs from the shangarila restaurant it measures 22 feet 
in diameter and is 5 inches high organizers said 
chefs beat 5000 eggs sifted 1232 pounds of flour and added 220 
pounds of watermelon seeds and 88 pounds of sugar they also mixed 
in more than 2 tons of durian a pungent tropical fruit 
the giant cake has to cool for 48 hours before it can be cut up 
and sold on sunday it is expected to be divided into 10000 pieces 
which will sell for 350 each with the proceeds going to charity 
