<TEXT>
the government said friday that its chief 
economic forecasting gauge turned up in july for the first time in 
three months posting a modest 02 percent gain which many 
economists interpreted as further evidence that there is no 
recession on the horizon 
the commerce department said the gain in the index of leading 
economic indicators followed no increase at all in june and a steep 
13 percent drop in may the biggest decline since late 1987 the 
index had risen 06 percent in april 
the government initially reported a month ago that the index had 
fallen in june as well marking the fourth time in five months that 
the index had fallen 
at the time the june report came out many analysts were 
convinced that the economy was on the verge of a recession however 
since that time a variety of government statistics have been revised 
to show more strength than previously believed 
these revisions have sent economists scurrying to scrap their own 
recession forecasts in favor of predictions calling for the economy 
to experience a slowdown in the second half of the year but come 
nowhere close to toppling into a recession 
bolstering that view the government issued its first look at 
august economic activity on friday with release of the unemployment 
statistics that report showed the jobless rate held steady at 52 
percent in july while the number of jobs after adjusting for 
strikes shot up by more than 200000 
allen sinai chief economist of the boston co said that the 
leading indicators the good employment report in august and a 
string of other government statistics in the past month showed that 
not only is there no imminent recession there isnt even a 
slowdown at the present time 
he predicted that overall economic growth as measured by the 
gross national product could advance at a rapid clip of between 3 
percent and 35 percent in the current julyseptember quarter 
that would be substantially faster than the 27 percent gnp 
growth rate from april through june but sinai predicted growth 
would slow in the final three months of the year reflecting an 
expected dip in auto sales after the flurry of modelyearending 
discount incentives offered in july and august 
michael evans head of a washington forecasting firm said he 
expected growth in the final half of the year would average 22 
percent while that would be down a percentage point from the 
firsthalf growth rate it would be enough to reach the 
administrations goal of 29 percent growth for all of 1989 
we are going to have a fine year for the economy evans said 
inflation started out badly but it has calmed down and now you 
would have to look pretty hard to find something you didnt like 
about this year 
analysts believe that with inflationary pressures easing because 
of a moderate slowdown in growth the federal reserve board has been 
able to achieve the socalled softlanding it was seeking 
in july five of the 11 leading indicators showed strength with 
the biggest positive push coming from an increase in the growth of 
the nations money supply 
analysts said that reflected the fact that the central bank began 
easing credit conditions slightly in june and july a development 
which has helped to push interest rates lower 
other sources of strength in the july report were a jump in 
consumer confidence the rise in stock market prices during the 
month an increase in plant and equipment orders and an increase in 
the backlog of unfilled manufacturing orders 
five indicators held back the overall increase the biggest 
negative factor was a decline in raw materials prices while lower 
inflation is generally seen as good for the economy the leading 
index considers it a drawback because it can signal falling demand 
other negative factors were a drop in orders for consumer goods 
an increase in weekly unemployment claims a fall in building 
permits and changes in business delivery times 
the 11th indicator the length of the average workweek showed no 
change from june to july 
the overall index stood at 1440 percent of its 1982 base of 100 
