<TEXT>
construction spending recorded a slight 
increase in july as strength in nonresidential building offset 
weakness in housing and government projects the commerce department 
reported friday 
the department said that spending rose by a tiny 002 percent a 
gain of 100 million putting the seasonally adjusted annual rate at 
4157 billion in july 
the increase followed a 09 percent decline in june and an 
advance of 08 percent in may 
while the july rebound was modest analysts said it offered at 
least the hope that the lengthy construction slump may be coming to 
an end 
allen sinai chief economist for the boston co noted that new 
home sales and construction starts for new homes were beginning to 
advance after a steep drop in the first part of 1989 he said that 
rebound would soon be reflected in the construction spending report 
and would help to lift the overall figure 
construction is on its way up because the lower mortgage rates 
have boosted sales he said 
sales of both new and existing homes fell sharply earlier in the 
year as mortgage rates climbed to a high of 1122 percent in late 
march rates then began falling and dropped as low as 981 percent 
in late july 
the federal home loan mortgage corp said that rates have been 
rising slightly in recent weeks and as of friday the national 
average for fixedrate mortgages stood at 1022 percent 
analysts said they did not believe the small increase in rates 
would be enough to dampen demand as long as mortgages dont rise 
much further 
in july all of the strength came in nonresidential 
construction which was up 09 percent to an annual rate of 997 
billion it was the third consecutive monthly gain in this sector 
following even stronger increases of 14 percent in june and 11 
percent in may 
the july increase was led by a 34 percent jump in spending for 
hotels and motels and a 31 percent gain in factory building 
projects 
residential construction edged down 02 percent to an annual rate 
of 1982 billion with singlefamily construction dipping 01 
percent while multifamily building was off a sharper 17 percent 
government construction spending fell by 12 percent in july to 
an annual rate of 809 billion as the biggest single government 
category highway construction dropped 4 percent 
the total construction figure was up a slight 12 percent from 
the level of building a year ago 
