a federal judge ruled friday in favor of united 
press international in a 12yearold libel case stemming from the 
death of a hawaiian man who linked a public official to organized 
crime 
us district judge charles richey said the complainant in the 
case failed to prove that the news report was false and the reporter 
was protected under the neutral reporting doctrine 
the case revolves around the death of a hawaiian environmental 
activist named george helm who a biweekly newspaper on june 15 
1977 strongly implied had been killed by local underworld 
figures 
dennis stone a upi reporter filed a story based on the 
newspaper report and an interview with the missing mans father the 
story said the missing activist had been threatened by a member of 
hawaiis board of land and natural resources named larry mehau 
according to george helms brother and father 
stones story also said the brother adolph identified mehau as 
the godfather of hawaiis underworld crime 
in a subsequent dispatch the same day stone wrote that the 
missing activist had told his brother adolph that he was planning 
to expose mehau and others 
the next day upi distributed a story detailing the hawaii 
governors strong defense of mehau and rejection of the biweekly 
newspaper story 
mehau quickly sued upi and lost two years later at the trial 
level on appeal the hawaii supreme court reversed the decision 
saying that stone acted with actual malice when he filed his two 
stories 
the case was remanded to the federal court in hawaii and removed 
to the disrict of columbia when upi went into bankruptcy here 
finally the case was switched from bankruptcy court to the 
district court and ended up with richey 
the disputed facts indicated the mehau has failed to prove 
by a fair preponderance of the evidence that stones reports are 
false said richey 
further the undisputed facts indicated that stones reports are 
absolutely protected under the neutral reportage doctrine which the 
court adopts herein for the first time in this circuit 
