<TEXT>
a defense consultant admitted friday that he 
sold unisys corp confidential bid information about a pentagon 
contract for 24750 and shared the proceeds with a fellow 
consultant 
william j sanda 53 pleaded guilty in us district court in 
alexandria va to a charge of conspiring to defraud the government 
in connection with the sale of information to unisys in 1987 about a 
100 million marine corps contract 
sanda who was president strategic systems institute of 
rockville md agreed to cooperate with the justice departments 
continuing investigation of defense department procurement fraud 
dubbed operation ill wind 
us district judge claude hilton scheduled sentencing for dec 
1 sanda could receive a fiveyear prison term and be fined up to 
250000 
his guilty plea signals that the justice department is preparing 
to expand its investigation to include current and former unisys 
executives based in eagan minn who sought confidential bid 
information on contract to build shelters for sophisticated 
communications and electronic equipment used by the marine corps 
unisys spokesman peter hynes declined to comment on sandas 
guilty plea said the company is cooperating with the probe 
sanda admitted that he agreed in march 1987 to be a front man 
for fellow consultant william parkin 
under their arrangement sanda agreed to take a third of the fee 
that unisys paid while parkin would receive the rest for providing 
the inside information 
parkin 65 has been sentenced to 26 months in prison and fined 
25000 for his role in the procurement scandal his cooperation 
with the investigation appears to have helped prosecutors bring the 
charge against sanda 
according to court papers sanda first approached an rca employee 
and offered to provide bid information about competitors sanda 
later reported to parkin that he was unable to work out a deal with 
rca one of several companies bidding on the contract 
sanda soon reported that a unisys corp marketing representative 
expressed interest in purchasing information 
the unisys corp official is not named but was identified in 
court papers unsealed earlier this year as marketing executive ralph 
hughes who hynes said left the company in december 1988 
sanda showed hughes a sample of bid information later reporting 
to parkin that hughes believed that sanda had an inside source 
at the pentagon according to court papers 
unisys paid sanda 19500 under a consulting contract on aug 19 
1987 according to the court papers sanda cheated parkin out of 
1000 by telling his fellow consultant unisys had paid 18000 
sanda gave parkin 12000 instead of 13000 which would have 
been the twothirds share of 19500 according to court papers 
parkin gave 6000 to thomas muldoon another defense consultant who 
court papers say was the source of the bid documents the court 
papers said 
muldoon has been implicated but not charged in the ill wind 
probe 
after receiving the first payment sanda reported that the unisys 
executive again identified in earlier court filings as hughes told 
him of a complaint to the navy that unisys had hired sanda to gain 
an unfair edge in the contract competition 
hughes had told sanda that unisys would have to fill a file 
cabinet with data to support the contention that sanda was doing 
technical work for the company according to court papers 
sanda later reported to parkin that a unisys vice president not 
identified in the court papers suggested firing sanda because of 
the complaint but the company decided against to avoid appearing to 
be engaged in wrongdoing 
sanda was paid another 5250 by unisys in november 1987 shortly 
after he had advanced parkin 4000 for more information 
the court document disclosed that sanda tried to sell bid 
information on navy and air force radar test kits to gould inc 
sanda told prosecutors he met with the president of goulds navcom 
division but was not hired by the company 
sanda told prosecutors that he gave the gould official 
information about the companys own bid to show he had an inside 
source but that the numbers were slightly off 
</TEXT>
