<TEXT>
the genetically altered virus released in a 
cabbage patch three weeks ago in the first test of its kind has been 
killing off the pest its supposed to fight and then dying off right 
on schedule scientists said 
the virus killed off all the cabbage looper insects that it was 
supposed to as part of the controlled experiment said h alan wood 
a virologist at the boyce thompson institute for plant research 
the institute is conducting the tests at cornell universitys 
agricultural experiment station in geneva and sprayed the field for 
a second time on thursday 
its very gratifying wood said our application technology 
was perfect everything was working just the way we predicted it 
would 
the aug 9 spraying made history as the first field release of a 
genetically altered virus in the united states the experiment was 
heralded as a milestone in the development of nonchemical methods 
of pest control 
the virus was genetically altered in the laboratory to be 
shortlived so that it would pose no threat of uncontrolled 
spreading 
samples that were taken one and two weeks after the first 
spraying show that the altered virus disappeared entirely from the 
900 cabbage plants where it was applied within according to wood 
but the virus that was ingested by the insects as well as 
whatever small amounts were absorbed into the soil will persist in 
decreasing amounts for another two years or so he said 
thursdays spraying was the second in a series of three scheduled 
for late this summer another 900 plants out of a total of 2700 in 
the test plot were sprayed 
the boyce thompson institute will monitor the field for two to 
three years to see how long the virus lives in the natural 
environment and to check for any movement of the virus according to 
an agreement with the us environmental protection agency 
