<TEXT>
the stock markets strength has presented a 
special challenge for a breed of wall streeters known as technical 
analysts how do you interpret charts and indicators when prices 
reach levels never seen before 
all but the newest of newcomers have experience dealing with this 
kind of situation from the day in early 1983 when the dow jones 
industrial average hit 1070 for the first time through the top at 
2722 in august 1987 
but all that practice wasnt enough for them to find any 
foolproof system for determining when a market at new peaks has 
further to go and when it is running out of steam 
most do agree that stocks now are nowhere near the extreme 
overvalued levels they reached two years ago so easy to spot 
now with the advantage of hindsight 
still a good many chartwatchers see cause for concern or at 
least caution heading into the last four months of 1989 
consider that most basic of measures for evaluating the market 
the ratio of stock prices to corporate earnings 
as measured by the leading market indexes the priceearnings 
ratio of a typical stock recently stood at about 13 to 1 down from 
about 20 to 1 in 1987 
pe ratios at 13 or so dont seem too high said martin 
zweig editor of the investment advisory letter the zweig forecast 
but what are peak earnings worth the business cycle has been 
up for seven years if were headed for recession stocks are 
anything but cheap 
zweig also notes that stocks are trading at more than 25 times 
their book value or theoretical worth if the companies they 
represent were liquidated only twice before has that ratio been 
higher just preceding the crashes of 1929 and 1987 
shortterm measures of sentiment or enthusiasm for stocks 
deteriorated expectably in august said philip roth technical 
analyst at the securities firm of shearson lehman hutton inc 
roth also observed however the trend is up we would become 
more negative on it only if volume stays high but prices fail to 
move ahead 
andrew gold at prudentialbache securities says several measures 
of momentum such as the cumulative number of stocks advancing 
minus those declining topped out a few weeks ago before the dow 
jones industrials and other market indicators pushed on to new highs 
this and other signals suggest the market is headed for an 
intermediateterm peak sometime this fall he contends 
but amid all the wariness some analysts cast ringing votes for 
further market gains 
at no time in the past 18 months have conditions been more 
bullish than they are today proclaims stephen leeb editor of the 
advisory letter indicator digest 
some might argue that stocks are no longer cheap since pes 
have risen while that is true it is also true that inflation has 
fallen 
what really counts is not the absolute level of pes but how 
high pes are relative to inflation by that measure stocks are 
about as cheap as they have been in the postwar period 
leeb says he believes the bull market has at least another year 
to run there are going to be reactions along the way maybe some 
as severe as 7 percent or 9 percent he concludes 
but the big rewards will continue to go to those who play the 
big trend rather than the shortterm swings 
</TEXT>
