the chicago mercantile exchange whose 
selfpolicing practices are under federal scrutiny has suspended 
four traders and fined them a total of 450000 for alleged 
violations during the 1987 stock market crash 
two of the traders were suspended for two years and ordered to 
return 44500 each to customers who were allegedly cheated 
the traders are accused of making prearranged transactions of 
stockindex futures in violation of exchange rules 
they allegedly cheated their customers by executing their orders 
privately for their own enrichment instead of in the open auction 
of the mercs standard amp poors 500 stockindex futures trading pit 
none of the traders has admitted or denied the allegations 
the stiff penalties suggest that the merc the worlds 
secondlargest futures market is taking a tougher stand against 
wrongdoing in the face of intense scrutiny of the industrys 
selfpolicing 
federal prosecutors on aug 2 announced indictments for alleged 
trading fraud against 45 traders and one clerk at the merc and the 
chicago board of trade the next day leo melamed chairman of the 
mercs executive committee promised to instill the fear of god 
in any traders who think of stealing 
most complaints against traders are settled before they get to a 
fullblown hearing and the case against the four traders was headed 
in that direction until the federal investigation became known 
afterward the merc broadened its probe to include more trades 
and brought added charges against the two main targets 
traders albert v furman iii and patrick j shannon jr were 
suspended from exchange membership for two years and ordered to make 
restitution of 44500 each 
furman was fined 125000 by the exchange in addition to 
prearranged trading the exchange found furman guilty of failing to 
fully answer all questions during an investigation of his case 
furman previously had been fined 125000 suspended two months 
and ordered to pay 127500 restitution in connection with other 
alleged improper stockindex futures trades made during the week of 
oct 19 1987 
shannon was fined 225000 in addition to his suspension 
peter shannon patricks brother was fined 50000 and suspended 
from exchange membership for two months 
sidney l rabin was also fined 50000 and suspended from 
exchange membership for two months 
stockindex futures are contracts for future delivery of groups 
of stocks futures traders can use stockindex futures to hedge 
against losses on actual stock market investments or simply to 
speculate on the prices of the underlying stocks 
