<TEXT>
the internal revenue service has proposed settling 
nelson bunker and carolyn hunts back tax bill for about 200 
million less than onethird of the 700 million the government 
originally sought 
grover hartt iii attorney representing the irs in the hunts 
bankruptcy case said thursday he had proposed the 200 million 
settlement to his superiors in washington dc 
us bankruptcy judge harold abramson thursday gave attorneys for 
bunker and his wife 30 days to hammer out details of the settlement 
with the irs 
the agreement in principle is a breakthrough in the nearly 
yearold bankruptcy negotiations of bunker hunt whose financial 
troubles stem in part from a scheme by hunt and his brother william 
herbert hunt to control the silver market in 1979 and 1980 
hunt and his wife filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection last 
september to defend themselves from a string of lawsuits and claims 
for back taxes interest and penalties arising in part from the 
silver scheme 
we are proposing to settle because we feel it is in the 
governments best interest economically hartt said the 
rationale is it is economically beneficial to get 80 percent of 100 
today than it is to get 100 percent of 50 a year from now 
russell l munsch attorney for bunker hunt declined to discuss 
terms of the deal saying that is still in negotiations 
the decision to settle the case comes one week after testimony in 
the 300 million tax trial involving bunker and his brothers 
william herbert and lamar was completed in washington dc 
us tax court judge jules g korner iii isnt expected to rule 
in that case before february 1990 
if the irs settles bunker and herberts tax liability before a 
judgment is rendered in the 1982 tax trial it could mean that the 
tax trial was a futile effort said michael henke attorney who 
represented both brothers 
henke asked that the tax court ruling be expedited he said the 
case has cost the hunts about 35 million in attorneys fees and 
expenses 
under an order issued by the bankruptcy judge thursday creditors 
will be allowed to file competing reorganization plans in bunkers 
bankruptcy case beginning oct 1 until then creditors have to base 
their negotiations for debt repayment on the hunts reorganization 
plan 
the settlement being discussed between bunker and the irs would 
be similar to that already proposed in the bankruptcy of herbert and 
his wife nancy the irs says the couple owes 300 million in back 
taxes 
the irs contends the two brothers owe the agency a combined total 
of 1 billion in back taxes but has agreed to settle herberts case 
for about 150 million and bunkers for about 200 million 
in bunkers case the irs would receive 80 percent of a 
liquidating trust or about 110 million the agency would also get a 
90 million nondischargeable to be paid out of gifts inheritances 
and future income after bunker and his wife emerge from bankruptcy 
the couple would be allowed to keep their home and certain personal 
belongings hartt said 
