<DOCNO> AP890901-0208 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
aztec tribesmen were such fanatics about 
their game of patolli they would gamble anything from corn fields to 
families in order to win this ancient version of you bet your 
life 
three albuquerque men who have fashioned an update of the game on 
an 18inch by 18inch board are wagering mere money about 60000 
so far in their gamble that it will be a big seller 
the odds are about one in 1000 that board games will be a 
financial success says mike kimball a graphics artist at the 
albuquerque journal who with friends phil white and jim franchell 
designed a modernday patolli which means game of the mat and 
sells for 2995 in specialty game stores 
kimball says his father richard kimball a writer in prescott 
ariz was doing research for an article when he came across a 
reference to patolli about three years ago 
he suggested to us that it might be interesting to play but he 
could find no records of rules or anything just accounts by 
spaniards mike kimball says 
we decided to come up with some rules we felt maintained the 
spirit of the thing he says we kept refining it until we had a 
real playable game and we decided it would be a good thing to put on 
the market 
modernday patolli players compete to be the first to maneuver 
four game pieces around the padded vinyl playing mat to a center 
pyramid they must avoid capture while wagering precious stones the 
winner gets a pot of golden tiger eyes the most valued stones of 
all 
the players must know which stones to move when to block and for 
how long when to bargain with a captive what kind of bets to make 
but the strategy can change with a roll of the five wooden dice 
bare on one side one to five dots on the flip side 
the playing stones are polished red jasper black obsidian 
turquoise howlite and white quartz a throwback to the pebbles that 
aztec players used 
betting cards outline payoffs on four different bets cortez 
boast montezumas fate omen of the days and so speak the gods 
aztecs would wager just about anything they were so into 
gambling theyd wager jewels capes theyd wager their farms 
their kids their wives and occasionally themselves kimball says 
theyd put up their lives for a certain amount of money if 
they paid the guy back there would be no problem he says if 
they couldnt pay the guy back within a certain amount of time 
theyd become a slave to that personor they would be sacrificed 
but a slave is a pretty valuable thing and you wouldnt just waste 
him 
the playing mat developed by kimball and partners is rimmed on 
each side with 20 aztec day signs such as the alligator deer dog 
vulture wind house jaguar or death 
the mat has a series of squares shaped like a cross on which 
playing pieces are moved 
the cross shape was used by the aztecs on their mats and 
represented to them the universe and the four seasons of life 
birth and spring in the east adulthood and summer in the south 
autumn and old age in the west and winter and death in the north 
kimball says although he and his partners did not know the exact 
rules of the aztec game they were intrigued by its gambling aspects 
we played other games like parchisi and go but this 
incorporates gambling and it became a lot more exciting kimball 
says once we refined the whole idea of the game we decided it 
would make a good game to massproduce 
the partners had their mats printed and contacted other suppliers 
for game components the first run of 2000 games was produced in 
1988 and most are sold 
worldwide games a mailorder company in colchester conn has 
ordered 240 patollis to be featured in its 1990 catalogue kimball 
says other specialty stores have ordered samples 
individual orders for patolli have come from spokane wash to 
west peabody mass from japan to england to canada some european 
game merchants also have expressed intense interest kimball says 
according to them this is exactly what european yuppies are 
looking for 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

