<TEXT>
china has set up a special commission to tackle 
the increasingly serious problem of factories failing to pay 
debts and taxes the official china daily said friday 
the report said the team to be headed by finance minister wang 
bingqian will seek to assist enterprises in repaying debts that 
have risen to 1085 billion yuan or about 293 billion at current 
exchange rates 
wang told the first meeting of the commission that defaults in 
the staterun business sector have risen rapidly this year 
disrupting the economy and interfering with the state budget 
li guixian governor of the peoples bank of china was quoted by 
the daily as saying defaults had intensified the acute shortage of 
funds and reduced factories working capital 
it said the governments austerity policies which have reduced 
construction projects and cut back on available credit and the 
refusal of some firms to pay taxes are reasons for the default 
problem 
li said that in the coming months banks will provide loans to 
companies with sound economic records to help clear their debts 
the daily said that as of the end of june chinas industrial and 
commercial banks had already provided loans to clear 8 billion yuan 
bank experts say many companies with large stockpiles of raw 
materials and products must also strive to move their stocks in 
order to pay their debts the daily said 
the report said the daqing oil and chemical factory one of 
chinas largest enterprises had been seriously affected by defaults 
from subsidiary companies it said that by the end of july 1100 
