<TEXT>
dow jones amp co said friday it is preparing to 
put an overthecounter market stock into its transportation average 
because a wave of mergers and buyouts is making it impossible to 
find enough big transport companies on the new york stock exchange 
it would be the first time any of the three dow jones averages 
industrials utilities and transportations has included a stock 
that was not traded on the new york stock exchange 
ual corp could be the next nyse stock to disappear from the dow 
jones average of 20 transportation stocks ual parent of united 
airlines has received a 619 billion bid from investor marvin 
davis a joint bid of more than 65 billion from uniteds pilots 
union management and british airways also reportedly was being 
formulated 
the overthecounter market is a network of dealers that trades 
issues by computer over phone lines without any central exchange 
overthecounter companies generally are smaller than those listed 
on the new york stock exchange and many are regarded as more 
speculative because they have not had the opportunity to establish 
records as seasoned businesses 
preparations for adding an overthecounter stock have been going 
on at least since january but have gained urgency with the dealings 
over ual 
were not going to do this until we have to do it but we 
wanted to make sure people were prepared for it said dan hinson 
an assistant managing editor at dow jones wall street journal in 
a week united could be gone 
yellow freight system inc and roadway services inc are among 
the overthecounter candidates to replace the next nyse stock that 
drops out said charles stabler an editorial consultant to dow 
jones 
the industry body that oversees overthecounter trading welcomed 
dow jones decision 
this is just another example and testimonial to the stocks that 
trade in nasdaq said john t wall executive vice president for 
marketing and market services at the washingtonbased national 
association of securities dealers 
at the new york stock exchange spokeswoman sharon gamsin said 
that while mergers and acquisitions have taken away some stocks the 
nyses total listings were at a record level 
seven stocks have dropped out of the dow jones average of 20 
transportation stocks and been replaced since the end of 1986 
twa dropped out in october 1988 when its chairman and owner carl 
icahn took the company private most recently nwa parent of 
northwest airlines dropped out in july when it was bought by a 
group led by investor alfred checchi 
the transportation average traces its origins to 1884 when dow 
jones amp co began occasionally reporting on an index of 11 
representative stocks most of which were railroad companies in 
1897 the company began separate indexes for railroad and industrial 
stocks 
the railroad average was renamed the transportation average in 
1970 to reflect its changing composition it now consists mainly of 
airlines trucking companies and a handful of railroads 
