<TEXT>
the japanese government said friday the nations 
surplus in the broadest measure of trade fell in july for the fifth 
month in a row 
the announcement came as president bush and japanese prime 
minister toshiki kaifu discussed trade in washington 
japans current account surplus which includes merchandise 
trade shipping tourism and investment income fell 183 percent 
from its level of a year earlier to 531 billion the finance 
ministry said 
car and steel exports were down while computer and business 
machine imports were up 
japans surplus in trade alone a narrower measure declined 
nearly 20 percent to 697 billion in july from a year earlier the 
ministry said 
government officials hope the recent trend will help japan repeat 
last years performance when it cut its current account surplus 87 
percent to 795 billion 
meeting with kaifu in washington bush said i share the prime 
ministers belief that while japan is noted as an exporting 
superpower the time has also come for japan to be an importing 
superpower 
kaifu said japan recognized that trade imbalances were a source 
of irritation and said his country would continue to make efforts 
for expanding imports 
fridays figures show that in july a booming economy at home 
continued to drive japans growth while exports lagged 
japans imports jumped to 16 billion 135 percent higher than 
in july of last year imports of computers business machines and 
textile products were strong ministry officials said 
exports inched up 03 percent from a year earlier to 23 billion 
exports of cars declined 53 percent and steel exports declined 37 
percent compared to last year 
american and japanese officials will meet monday and tuesday in 
tokyo to discuss structural ways to reduce their bilateral 
imbalance japan will probably ask the united states to reduce its 
budget deficit which economists say fuels its trade deficit 
us officials may ask japan to stimulate its domestic economy to 
increase imports and encourage its people to spend rather than save 
after adjustment for seasonal fluctuations the current account 
surplus grew to 405 billion in july from 292 billion in the 
previous month 
the surplus in merchandise trade declined to 547 billion in 
july from 575 billion the previous month 
both exports and imports were measured when contracts were 
settled the finance ministry each month makes a separate 
announcement of trade statistics that are compiled when goods pass 
through customs 
</TEXT>
